ApplicationSubmissionInfoGrp.FormAndInfoAndMaterialsTxt: Most of the Foundation's grants are through individual awards or awards under authorization that involve program centers, coordinating centers or hubs. These issues and topics of interest are described on the Foundation's internet site (www.rwjf.org). The competitive grant application process begins with a call for proposal or a request for proposal, which can be found on the Foundation's internet site. Most of the Foundation's grants are solicited by the Foundation, and generally either fit the Foundation's explicit fields of interest within health and health care, or advance the Foundation's overarching goal of building a Culture of Health in America. Applicants may initiate the grant process by submitting a three-page, electronic brief proposal using the application form provided online.
ApplicationSubmissionInfoGrp.SubmissionDeadlinesTxt: No deadlines, except when Foundation issues a call for proposal (CFP) or request for proposal (RFP).
ApplicationSubmissionInfoGrp.RestrictionsOnAwardsTxt: The Robert Wood Johnson Foundation's mission is to improve the health and health care of all Americans and to build a Culture of Health throughout the country - enabling all in our diverse society to lead healthy lives, now and for generations to come. To help Americans lead healthier lives and get the care they need, the Foundation makes grants to identify and pursue new opportunities to address persistent health challenges and to anticipate and respond to emerging challenges. For many years, the Foundation has focused the majority of its grant making in specific fields such as health care coverage, childhood obesity, public health, and improving the value of health care. GeneralExplanationGrp.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: PART IX-A, SUMMARY OF DIRECT CHARITABLE ACTIVITIES
GeneralExplanationGrp.MediumExplanationTxt: 1. Transforming Health and Health Care Systems - Programs, projects and activities that aim to strengthen the ways in which community health systems work together to meet the needs of the people they serve. In addition, there are also programs, projects and activities to provide data analysis of state and national-level coverage issues, and promote enrollment information and assistance to children and their families. $ 8,092,662 2. General Outreach and Support - Programs which support improving health care value, promoting prevention, growing the field of health and health care leadership, supporting communications and policy projects, and synthesizing and spreading research and evaluation findings through the web, social media and other means. $ 7,377,348 3. Leadership for Better Health - Programs and activities to bring together leaders from all walks of life, including the health professions, and develop their skills to lead the change necessary to build a Culture of Health. Includes programs that develop health policy scholars, encourage youth to pursue health careers, and partner community leaders with researchers. $ 6,639,292 4. Research Evaluation Learning - Programs and activities to expand our nation's evidence base on the many factors which shape health, and what types of policy and system changes have the greatest potential for impact. Includes signature research programs helping to identify the root causes of health disparities in America, and potential solutions to improve health, equity, and well-being; evaluations assessing the impact of our funding; activities to embed learning throughout our decision-making; and efforts leveraging decades of research to assist policymakers at the federal, state, and local levels in their efforts to safeguard and improve health in the communities they serve. $ 6,228,979 5. Other Targeted Programs - Programs, projects, and activities to ensure all children and their families have an equitable opportunity to attain optimal physical, social, and emotional development and well-being; to create the conditions that allow communities and their residents to reach their best possible well-being; to achieve health equity by ensuring everyone has a fair and just opportunity to live a healthier life; to create and promote innovations that may result in solutions at the cutting edge of health and health care; to find innovative ideas from other countries that could help improve our health here at home; to support locally based projects that promote the health and health care of New Jerseyans; and to support research, evaluation, learning and communications efforts that can improve the nation's health. $16,157,398 Total direct charitable activities during the tax year. $44,495,679
